{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:00:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:00:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1510"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.46,0.37,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35732"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1510"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20569"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"329"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3119"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/35732"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old man presents with a one-month history of an intermittent swelling in his neck, which can become painful and tender when swollen (image). He has not noticed any lumps anywhere else in this region. He is otherwise fit and well, denying any unintentional weight loss, night sweats or anorexia. His history is significant for depression for which he takes escitalopram, and he is not on any other regular medications. On examination, the lump is non-tender, well-circumscribed with smooth margins and no fixation to the underlying tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma","Metastatic disease","Submandibular duct stone","Branchial cyst","Epidermoid cyst"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe swelling is in the region of the submandibular gland. The gland has become enlarged because of a \u003Cstrong\u003Estone obstructing the salivary duct\u003C/strong\u003E, a condition referred to sialolithiasis. Sialolithiasis most commonly affects the submandibular gland (80%), followed by parotid glands (20%), and very rarely sublingual glands (\u0026lt;1%). Increased stone formation in the submandibular gland may arise due to its increased production of mucin and calcium. Typically, sialolithiasis will present asymptomatically with cyclical enlargement of the lump upon eating, or even thinking, about food due to increased salivary production during the cephalic phase of digestion. However, it may present as painful if there is distension of the capsule, which is likely in this instance given the size of the swelling pictured.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphoma may present as an isolated painless swelling of a single lymph node in a young adult, but is less likely to cause cyclical painful swelling. He also denies any systemic symptoms, making both Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma and metastatic disease less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBrachial cleft cysts may also present as a painless swelling in young adults without any other constitutional symptoms, but will not cause the cyclical painful swelling as described in the stem above.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sialolithiasis often presents as swelling that enlarges on eating"],"references":["Bova, R 2006, \u2018A guide to salivary gland disorders\u2019, MedicineToday, vol. 7, no. 2, pp. 44\u201348, viewed 30 June 2021, \u003Chttps://entthyroid.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Medicine-Today-Salivary-Gland-Disorders-Ron-Bova.pdf\u003E.","Hammett, J \u0026 Walker, C 2019, Sialolithiasis, StatPearls Publishing, Treasure Island, viewed 30 June 2021, \u003Chttps://europepmc.org/article/NBK/nbk549845\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20569"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19903"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19903"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/84dcadf3-f054-4517-9d9b-43563ab2b861.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/84dcadf3-f054-4517-9d9b-43563ab2b861.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":300,"height":300}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/20569"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-05-07T12:04:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-05-07T12:04:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1510"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35732"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.